The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 The board of Shriram Investments has recommended a final dividend of 15 per cent for the year 2004-05, in addition to an interim payout of 10 per cent announced earlier. The total dividend of the company stands at 25 per cent. Shriram Investments has posted a 29 per cent increase in net profit at Rs 46.84 crore. The increased earning came on the back of a 27.8 per cent rise in total income at Rs 342.93 crore against Rs 268.32 crore in the previous fiscal.

 Shree Cement has signed an agreement with the Dhunseri group to jointly set up a cement plant in Assam. The unit will be built at an investment of Rs 250 crore and will commence production in two years after the allotment of limestone mines and land are completed. 

 Southern Petrochemical Industries Corporation (Spic) has posted a net profit of Rs 9.41 crore for 2004-05 compared with a net loss of Rs 9.41 crore in the previous fiscal. For the fourth quarter, the company has suffered a loss of Rs 87.75 crore against a net profit of Rs 114.96 crore in the same period previous year.

 HCL infosystems has allotted 2,510 shares of Rs 10 each under an employees stock option scheme. The company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange that its committee of directors (share allotment) has recommended the allotment.

 KPIT Infosystems plans to raise $11-million long-term loan from the International Finance Corporation to fund its expansion plans, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. 

 Prime Securities will buy back 22.27 per cent of the existing paid-up equity capital. The company board has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange about the buyback of the fully-paid shares of Rs 5 each at a price not exceeding Rs 50 up to Rs 5 crore.

 Gammon India has bagged the Rs 800-crore Mumbai-Nashik road project of the National Highways Authority of India on a build, operate and transfer basis. The project will be one of the largest road projects of the country under public-private partnership.

 Vishal Exports Overseas plans to set up a 100-mega-watt wind power project at a cost of Rs 550 crore. These wind farms will be set up over a period of two years and the project would be completed in three modular phases, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange.

 Satyam Computer Services has been selected by Bausch amp; Lomb Eyecare (India) Pvt Ltd for its enterprise solution.

